It's throwback Thursday, what advice would you give to your 6 year old self?

I would say...:

Kid, you won’t stay little and scrawny forever. 

You won't wear hand-me-downs  and funny-looking clothing forever.

It’s not about where you start, it’s where you finish.

Don’t judge yourself in comparison to others.  Never ask for what you’re not willing to give.

Don’t judge someone till you’ve walked I  their shoes. Things are not always what they appear.

Don’t worry about getting knocked down. Focus on getting back up as quickly as possible.

Persistence ultimately pays off.

Listen to all advice and criticism, but know when to ignore them.

Once you realize that you truly know nothing, life’s real education begins.

Learn to accept unconditional love, and to give it back tenfold in return.

Invest yourself only in those willing to invest themselves in you. Toxic people and “takers” will suck your energy dry.

Pay more attention to what people do, not what they say. 

Dreams do come true, but not without actions. People usually regret the things they DIDN’T do. 

Good things may come to those who wait, but not to those who wait too late.

You can’t change anyone, except yourself.

The people who truly love you don’t see all the flaws you see. 

Celebrate your victories in life, even the small ones.

Sometimes love is not enough.

Don’t be afraid to jump in. Nobody ever made history by playing it safe.

Happiness is a lifelong journey, and it isn’t just the most important thing in life; it’s the only thing that matters.

Life’s too short to work for the money.

Surround yourself with people who make you want to be your best self.

What goes around comes around. 

Think before you speak, You’re never quite as smart as you think you are. 

If you want something, just ask. The worst thing anyone can say is no.

Parenthood isn’t that hard if you do what you wish your parents would have done for you.

People come into your life for a reason, a season, or a lifetime. Learning how to figure out which is which, and when to let go.

Good health is the greatest gift of all.  virtues #childrens #kindness #love #wellness #lifejourney #kindness #growth

If you’re a new follower who’s curious about me and what I’m about, this post is for you.

I’m dedicated single dad of a well-adapted,
high- performing student in her 3rd year in college. Expecting to graduate at 20 years old.

I just saw her grade, (18 credits this semester 3.9 GPA)  I felt very proud, and it also made me think of the experience we had at @archerschoolforgirls  an elite, prestigious school for girls in the Brentwood area. She went there for middle school and part of her high school. 

They  tried to convince me that my daughter was going nowhere fast, and I was a terrible a  parent,  I was even ordered to read a couple of parenting books.  They tried to destroy her self-confidence and crush her spirit.  Fortunately,  my guiding light has been to be the father I wished I had.

I’m sharing this to remind parents that nobody knows your child better than you do. 

Happy holiday season everyone.  #girldad #singledad #education #parenting #collegestudent #daughters #holidayseason #singleparent
